Georeferencing could be performed for the 48 children who had available home addresses and lived in the urban area of Medellín. The clustering of cases was evident at two sites that were considered of higher risk: the neighborhoods of the northeastern area and District 13 to the west of the city (Figure 2
). No significant increase in CAP cases caused by M. pneumoniae was found at a specific time point during the study period (Figure 3
).
